        \item Draw the cycle on a $T$ - $S$ diagram.
    \end{anum}

In the Knudsen method of measuring vapour pressure $p$ from a liquid
containing molecules of mass m at temperature $T$, the liquid is placed in
the bottom of a container that has a small hole of area $A$ at the top, and the container is placed on top of a scale. The weight $Mg$ of the setup is measured \textit{over time}. How can you find the vapour pressure from this reading? If you can't get it exactly, an estimate up to a dimensionless constant is good as well.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=3.5cm]{knudsen_vapor.png}
\end{center}

Estimate the net heat flux density P between two parallel plates at distance $L$ from each other, which are at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$, respectively. The space between the plates is filled with a monoatomic gas of number density $n$ and of mass $m$. You may assume the following:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item The gas density is so low that the mean free path $\lambda \gg L$;
        \item $T_1 \gg T_2$.
        \item When gas molecules bounce from the plates, they obtain the temperature of the respective plates (for instance, this will happen if they are absorbed/bound for a short time by the molecules of the plate, and then released back into the space between the plates).
    \end{enumerate}
